---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Nav from "../../components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import RevealScript from "../../components/RevealScript.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Jamestown Area Schools Brand Book — Brittany Childs"
  description="Case study for the Jamestown Area Schools brand book and identity standards system."
>
  <Nav />

  <main>
    <section class="section">
      <div class="eyebrow">Brand Systems</div>
      <h1 class="display" style="font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4.5rem);">
        Jamestown Area Schools Brand Book
      </h1>
      <p class="lead">
        A comprehensive multi-school identity standards project developed to
        create greater consistency across district communications while also
        establishing CABOCES’ first formal workflow for brand-book development.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section feature-grid">
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="meta">Client: Jamestown Area Schools</div>
        <div class="meta">Role: Graphic Design, Brand Systems Development</div>
        <div class="meta">Scope: Multi-school brand standards book</div>
        <div class="meta">Context: Educational communications / institutional identity</div>
      </div>

      <div class="frame reveal">
        <img
          src="https://placehold.co/1600x1000/e9e1d7/1f1b18?text=Jamestown+Brand+Book+Hero"
          alt="Jamestown Area Schools brand book placeholder"
        />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section about-grid">
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">Overview</div>
        <h2 class="project-title">Building structure where none previously existed.</h2>
        <p>
          This project began as more than a design assignment. It required the
          development of an organized standards system for multiple schools,
          along with a clear internal process for how CABOCES approaches
          large-scale brand-book work moving forward. Because no established
          workflow existed, the project demanded both design execution and
          systems thinking from the ground up.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">Purpose</div>
        <h2 class="project-title">Creating consistency across a broader school identity system.</h2>
        <p>
          Jamestown Area Schools needed a framework that could support multiple
          schools and identities while still feeling coherent as part of a
          larger district environment. The goal was to create standards that
          could guide future communications, reinforce visual consistency, and
          provide a usable reference point for long-term stewardship.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="eyebrow">The Challenge</div>
      <div class="process-strip reveal">
        <div>
          <strong>Multiple Schools</strong>
          <p>
            The system needed to account for multiple identities and contexts
            while still maintaining cohesion across the broader brand structure.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <strong>No Existing Process</strong>
          <p>
            CABOCES had not previously developed a formal brand book at this
            scale, so the workflow itself had to be built during the project.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <strong>Long-Term Usefulness</strong>
          <p>
            The standards needed to be practical, clear, and durable enough to
            support future communication work beyond the initial deliverable.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section feature-grid">
      <div class="frame reveal">
        <img
          src="https://placehold.co/1600x1000/e9e1d7/1f1b18?text=Brand+System+Layouts"
          alt="Brand system layout placeholder"
        />
      </div>

      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">Approach</div>
        <h2 class="project-title" style="font-size: 2rem;">
          Brand standards as both a visual and organizational system.
        </h2>
        <p>
          The work focused on building a standards document that could operate
          as a true system rather than simply a visual reference. That meant
          thinking carefully about structure, hierarchy, consistency, and how
          the material would actually be used over time. The process balanced
          identity clarity with flexibility, ensuring the final book could
          support real-world communication needs across different schools and
          stakeholders.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="eyebrow">Key Considerations</div>
      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card reveal">
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="meta">Systems Thinking</div>
            <h3 class="project-title">Organized Structure</h3>
            <p>
              The brand book needed to feel intuitive and easy to navigate, with
              a structure that made standards clear and accessible for future use.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card reveal">
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="meta">Institutional Identity</div>
            <h3 class="project-title">Consistency Across Schools</h3>
            <p>
              The project required balancing individual school character with a
              broader sense of coherence across the district system.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card reveal">
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="meta">Practical Application</div>
            <h3 class="project-title">Usable Standards</h3>
            <p>
              The final deliverable was designed to support future decision-making,
              not just serve as a presentation artifact.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section about-grid">
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">Role</div>
        <h2 class="project-title">Leading both the design work and the process design.</h2>
        <p>
          In addition to shaping the visual system and standards document, this
          project involved defining how the work itself would be organized and
          executed. That included building a process where no prior model
          existed, creating a foundation CABOCES can apply to future branding
          initiatives.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">Impact</div>
        <h2 class="project-title">A flagship systems project within an educational context.</h2>
        <p>
          The Jamestown Area Schools brand book represents a meaningful step
          beyond one-off design deliverables. It reflects a more strategic mode
          of communication design—one focused on stewardship, scalability, and
          the long-term value of consistent institutional identity.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="eyebrow">Selected Deliverables</div>
      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card reveal">
          <div class="frame">
            <img
              src="https://placehold.co/1200x1500/e9e1d7/1f1b18?text=Cover+Concept"
              alt="Brand book cover placeholder"
            />
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="meta">Core Deliverable</div>
            <h3 class="project-title">Brand Book Framework</h3>
            <p>
              A structured standards document designed to guide identity use and
              future communications across a multi-school environment.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card reveal">
          <div class="frame">
            <img
              src="https://placehold.co/1200x1500/e9e1d7/1f1b18?text=System+Pages"
              alt="Brand standards spread placeholder"
            />
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="meta">Standards Development</div>
            <h3 class="project-title">System Guidelines</h3>
            <p>
              Pages focused on organizing identity guidance into a form that is
              clear, readable, and useful in practice.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card reveal">
          <div class="frame">
            <img
              src="https://placehold.co/1200x1500/e9e1d7/1f1b18?text=Application+Examples"
              alt="Brand application placeholder"
            />
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="meta">Future Application</div>
            <h3 class="project-title">Communication Alignment</h3>
            <p>
              The system was built to support stronger consistency across future
              district and school-facing materials.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section feature-grid">
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">Why It Matters</div>
        <h2 class="project-title" style="font-size: 2rem;">
          A design project that demonstrates strategy, stewardship, and scale.
        </h2>
        <p>
          This case study highlights more than layout or visual polish. It shows
          the ability to think systemically, work within institutional contexts,
          and create structures that help organizations communicate more
          consistently over time. It is a strong example of design functioning
          as both a visual discipline and an operational one.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="frame reveal">
        <img
          src="https://placehold.co/1600x1000/e9e1d7/1f1b18?text=Final+Presentation+Spread"
          alt="Final brand book presentation placeholder"
        />
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
  <RevealScript />
</BaseLayout>